WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:18.000
This is Emily Crosby on December 10th, 2015, and we're with Freddie Greene at the Library of Congress.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:27.000
This is part of the Civil Rights History Project, and it's co-sponsored by the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:31.000
And John Bishop is also here.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.000
Thanks so much again for joining us.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:39.000
Can you start by telling us when and where you were born and about your family?

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:51.000
Sure. Well, I was born in Greenwood, Mississippi, which is in the heart of the Mississippi Delta in 1945, February 15, 1945.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:01:04.000
And I grew up in a large black family that both my parents were originally from Mississippi and always lived there.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:20.000
My father in the early 60s had been involved often on with the NAACP, so my father was a small business person, had a house painting business where the majority of his work was.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:25.000
And I was close to the White community.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:35.000
And my mother had taught school up until the time she married my father and she married my father when she was 29.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:43.000
So at that stage in time, being 29 and getting married was kind of late in life.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:51.000
Well, she talked about growing up in Greenwood. She actually grew up in Greenwood. She grew up in the exact same house that I grew up in.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:02:01.000
Actually, my great-grandmother had owned and built that house.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:09.000
And my mother came after she married my father. My father was a farmer.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:23.000
And he carried her to live on the farm. And to my mother who had grown up in Greenwood, even though Greenwood was a very small thing, farming just was not for her.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:31.000
She said it was just too quiet. It was too dark and it was nobody to talk to.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:42.000
Now, she had grown up in Greenwood in the 1600s of a Howard Street, which was just across the railroad from downtown Greenwood.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:48.000
So all of her life, she's pretty much been a setting girl.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:57.000
And she went to the church to Wesley, which is used to say that she and her mother went to Wesley every time the church doors open.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:01.000
And the church was like two blocks from where they lived.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:15.000
My mother had had kind of interesting life. She basically grew up in that house. Her mother owned a little florist shop and her father owned a barber shop.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:20.000
So that was like a few blocks away. So they were little business people.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:30.000
But when my mother was a child, she had had a brother and the brother had kicked in the head by a horse directly in front of the house.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:38.000
So as a result, it was just the two of them. And my mother says that her mother became overly protective of her.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:45.000
So this was a traumatic experience of losing a child at five years old directly in front of your house.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:48.000
And it means something that you wouldn't think that would happen.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:04:00.000
You know, your two little kids are out front playing, but somebody ties a horse and wagon to the tree that's outside.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:07.000
And then, inadvertently, these two little kids go to close. And the horse kicks my uncle's in the head.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.000
And so that's the end.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:16.000
Yeah, so it was very, very traumatic. And my mother, so from then on, my mother was the only child.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:22.000
And then she just went back with some horse all the time to church, however.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:25.000
That's how she was allowed to do. She went to church.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:31.000
And doing those years in Greenwood, there was no...

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:36.000
The only school that she went to was a private school that she went to.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:45.000
Then she went away to go to high school. And she went to Tougaloo to high school doing the...

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:49.000
This one is because at that time Tougaloo had a high school.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:55.000
She went there to high school. And she also went there to stay there on the college and stuff.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:04.000
And then she came back to live with her mother and live there while she taught school up until she married my father.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
That's an indication, I guess, of how a lot of parents must have lived.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.000
Well, I think that...

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:15.000
Also, you have to consider the fact that it was only one child.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:29.000
And I guess they were better off than most people, because you're talking about probably less than two percent of the black people in the flow county own properties.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:41.000
So just to the fact that her mother had inherited this house from her mother, you know, that did give her a little bit of a privilege.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:48.000
Now my father in return had grown up on the farm. He and his brother. And he only had one brother.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:54.000
And my father could relate to you because my father went to...

00:05:54.000 --> 00:06:02.000
When he got ready to go to high school and to college, he went to Alcorn.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:10.000
Out in the woods. And my daddy used to say that when they went to college, they went in the fall.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:15.000
And they didn't come home to the spring. So you stayed through the entire year.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:21.000
All of that, you spent it all that school. You could not come home. I mean, transportation.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:30.000
So daddy says that the school would bring the wagon down to the train station to pick up the trunks.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:35.000
And then the boys and the girls would all follow the wagon back to school.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:42.000
So that was his whole... But it was like, it was nothing but country.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:50.000
It's still nothing. But that's... So that was his idea of Lohmann.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:57.000
And he didn't like it. He thought it was too rural. He wanted to see something else.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:04.000
And he convinced his folks. They sent him a one-year. He went to Tuskegee Institute to...

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
To take up shoemaking because he wanted to do something.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:13.000
And he didn't... He said he really didn't want to farm, but he wanted to do something.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:21.000
But he wanted to work for himself. I mean, he had a thing that he did not want to work for anybody.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:23.000
Did his parents own their own farm?

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:31.000
They own their farm, yeah. And out in the area where he lived, his family owned there.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:37.000
There was another two other black families around that also owned their land.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:47.000
And we were talking about... Because my father was born in 1900. His brother was born in 1898.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:54.000
So we were talking about an older generation of people.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:03.000
And it's... Basically, there were these little pockets where families had own land.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:08.000
And they had held very, very tight. I mean, people lived off the land.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:15.000
They farm, they raise animals. They had gardens and all.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:22.000
I mean, dad used to talk about the time that he and his brother saw somebody stealing the truck.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:27.000
But they didn't realize that the guys were... They was his truck, that the guys were stealing.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:34.000
They saw these men struggling, pushing this truck. They got off the back porch to go out to help.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:40.000
And as they started down the road, the guys took off running.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:46.000
And then they said, we wouldn't until they got close. They realized that that's why they were running.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:51.000
It was their truck, that they would take it.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:54.000
So that's what...

00:08:54.000 --> 00:09:02.000
So that's... I mean, that's the way it was. People helped people.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:07.000
Did your grandparents still have that farm when you were a child?

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:16.000
Well, my grandparents did. My uncle sold it. My grandparents, three of my grandparents died.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:26.000
The year was first grade, which was in 1951, died in 1951. The fall of 1951 and the other two died.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:33.000
They were doing the spring in 1952. And yeah, it was first grade.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:41.000
My uncle actually sold the farm probably in the late 50s.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:50.000
Because his uncle was one of the two black postmen in Greenwood.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.000
That's a good job.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:56.000
It was an extremely good job. I mean, they were like that.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:03.000
They used to say that uncle and this other man, Mr. Dickson, was the postman.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:10.000
And they had very, very good jobs. And so did there was another man, Mr. Thompson, who cleaned up the post office.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:14.000
And all of these were definitely considered to be very, very good jobs.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:18.000
Because they basically had benefits.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:24.000
And my father always contributed towards his social security.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:31.000
And my daddy had a strong thing about that he felt that that was going to support him as he grew older.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:38.000
Because my parents had grown up. My father, 1900, my mother was born in 1907.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:47.000
Of course, they knew about history before social security and how people did not have any food and stuff

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:52.000
and have the ability to support themselves. And obviously, if they weren't social security,

00:10:52.000 --> 00:11:00.000
there were definitely people working that made in somebody's house and in field hands had no pension plans.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.000
And were not eligible for social security?

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:05.000
And were not eligible for social security.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:08.000
So there wouldn't have been that many people in the community doing it.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:11.000
So that's what kind of unusual...

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:17.000
Well, yeah, I mean, my daddy did it. And so did he had another good friend.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:23.000
And Mr. Hilton, who also had another little business.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:34.000
I think that, and they both used to talk back-and-forth with other people who had small businesses trying to encourage a person to do it.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:42.000
And the real question and what daddy always said was that the question of whether this was going to work.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:53.000
Because it was talking about something that you were told about that you had never experienced and never knew anyone else who had it experience.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:12:04.000
And you had to have faith that when you're writing, doing out this form and depositing money over in an account that's supposed to be there for you,

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:09.000
when you receive, when you reach the certain age to be able to retire.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:16.000
And that daddy had faith. And his friend did, but as he said, most people didn't.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:24.000
From time to time, when he had other painters to work for him, most of them, no one wanted to do that.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:30.000
Because as far as they were concerned, you're given your money away.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:34.000
Did you have any experience with how it worked or when it really did work?

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:42.000
No, no one had any experience. I mean, you're talking about, in 35, when this is really first being introduced.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:57.000
And that you also are talking about generation of most black people who didn't have much formal education and you're doing everything you can to survive.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:05.000
And no one is really providing you with huge amount of information on how this is working.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:12.000
This is all before the Internet.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
It's an act of faith.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:24.000
It's an act of faith. However, he just had faith that this was really going to work.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:34.000
And as it turns out, the Social Security process was probably one of the things that was able to help my father.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:45.000
Because as we began to, as a family, get involved in the movement, less and less jobs, people called that a fall.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:56.000
So as a result, in 1964, he literally had to retire on his Social Security because he was not getting work.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:00.000
People would not call him for a job.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:09.000
Now, the good thing is that it correlated with the same time that he was really eligible for Social Security.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:14.000
I mean, if he had been a younger person, it would have been much harder and stuff.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:27.000
And I think that that was the other advantage that I had with growing up with older parents that they had a little bit more advantage than people who were no fresh out much younger.

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:37.000
When the movement was being in the movement, strength, pressure against your family, they were in a position where they could withstand it.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:43.000
They could withstand it. They owned the house and dad it was able to draw his Social Security.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:48.000
I mean, I think that that was that made life easier.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:54.000
Before we start talking about the movement, can you talk about what your schools were like and what happened?

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
Can you give us a picture of what dream was with life?

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:01.000
Well, now, consider that. I grew up on Howard Street.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:18.000
If you looked at a map then, the 600 block was, there was a railroad track that really separated the block that I lived in from downtown.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:30.000
So if the 500 block of Howard Street, there would have been a go-birds, there was a shoe store, so it's all downtown Greenwood that's going that way.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:37.000
We are also on the edge of the streets going. So that's going north.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:46.000
So if you then were talking about the East West, streets go over about four other blocks and then you're in the white neighborhood.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:58.000
So we are technically living on the, even though that's the oldest part of the city where I grew up, it's really on the edge of the black community when I was growing up.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:06.000
So we could technically at my house hear the white kids over at the playground, at the park.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:15.000
You could hear them in the park playing. So, I mean, so we're that close to that community.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:24.000
So the school, we all walked, all the black kids walked the school.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:31.000
And I do believe all the white kids walked the school except for the kids who lived outside the city limits.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:45.000
And that was always one of the big problems that my father had is that they used to say all the time they had school buses that they went around and picked up kids in the counties.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:52.000
White kids in the counties and brought them into school so that they went to better schools.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:58.000
That his tax dollars was really paying for that his children could go to.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:05.000
My schools were all segregated. The school books in my school came from the white school.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:13.000
So as white kids got new textbooks, they then shipped over textbooks to the black schools.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:28.000
And considering the fact that I started school in 1951, so you're talking about, and I graduated in 1963 and schools were still totally segregated in Greenwood.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.000
So much of Brown.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:39.000
Yeah, so much of urban Brown. I think they did not desegregate, even start desegregating the schools in Greenwood until 1970.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:42.000
Yeah, they didn't have freedom of choice.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:18:00.000
Yeah, yeah. So we basically went, but what did happen is after the Supreme Court decision, what Mississippi did do is they began to build high schools in small communities.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:17.000
Now Greenwood was one of the communities that had a high school. So as a result, a lot of black families that could send their children in, no found people to get for their kids to be able to stay with, to be able to go to high school.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:28.000
So people out in the county and people all like that, but that was something that you had to organize yourself. I mean, it was no system in that.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:35.000
If you were lucky enough to know somebody to be able to, for your kids to be able to stay with.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.000
Yeah.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:46.000
So after Brown, they did like you're talking about, they built a new school. At the same time, they actually started providing buses to bring black children from the county in the poor districts.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:47.000
Oh, yeah.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.000
It's one of those things they did after Brown.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:58.000
Yeah, well, they definitely built high schools. And the high school proud to Brown became the junior high school, and they built a new high school.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:02.000
And they just began to build high schools all around.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:07.000
Did they bring any of the county kids that they should be able to come to the county kids in the poor district?

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:19.000
No, what they did do in the early 60s is they built a county school for the kids. And then they had to go to the county school.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:28.000
So they did pick them up for the kids and have Amanda Elsie that they built in the 60s, yes.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:31.000
And that was solely for the county kids.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
Okay.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:40.000
What are some of your first few memories of race in the rare race?

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:48.000
Well, first is we didn't, we were, schools were all segregated.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:20:01.000
We only went downtown when, with our parents, when we went specifically to buy something, school clothes, when it's time to go.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:14.000
The whole process was that we went, what we call window shopping to look at things so that you went and looked in the one then we did that with mom and daddy.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:21.000
And one of the biggest things I remember is my folks always talked about keeping you safe.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:29.000
And they did not want to downtown. They didn't want you around different areas.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:36.000
And there was a block from where I lived. There was a guy who had a little corner store.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:44.000
And my father, it was a white guy. And my father didn't allow us to go in there because he said that the judges didn't treat people right.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:51.000
So he did not want to, you to deal with that.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:21:04.000
Growing up in a completely segregated community like that, you really don't, since there's no real reason to go downtown, my contact was with all black people most of the time.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:15.000
We had a telephone and we probably won a few people who had a straight, what's considered to be a straight line because a lot of people had what's called a party line.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:20.000
And there's like several different people who share the same line. And so as a result they do it.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:27.000
But my father said that for his business, he needed this private line. So he had this line.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:36.000
But the phone was strictly for business. It was where people called him about jobs and stuff.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:43.000
And we answered the phone, took messages and all of that for him. But the phone was clearly business.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:53.000
And occasionally somebody would come by to ask him about, come by to see him about work.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:22:03.000
As I said, and these were all white people. I did notice across the street from us, there were people who came by to pick up their mates.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:09.000
There were some people who picked up their mates and carried them back with them forwards to work.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:17.000
There were also people who dropped off the laundry that people did on and for folks. So it was all of that.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:23.000
But just coming directly in contact with white people, we just didn't do it.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:35.000
The superintendent of schools was always white. And the superintendent of schools used to come to the schools once a year for commencement.

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:45.000
And he would make out, he was always first on the program. And he would make his five or ten minute little speech and then he would accept.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:54.000
During the time when I was in high school, our football team was really good. And they were big eight champions.

00:22:54.000 --> 00:23:06.000
So that was the division that we actually played in. So what happened is that they would occasionally bring in the white football team to watch.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:15.000
And they set up their special bleaches down for the boys from that team to watch the team and play football.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:24.000
And then they, I mean, football is big in the South. So they used to do that. So they'd succumbed by for that.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:31.000
But there was no interaction. Like I could not tell you a single person's name.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:38.000
There was no white person that was growing up at the same time. Because I just had no interaction with them whatsoever.

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:47.000
And my father was determined that we were not going to work. I mean, a lot of people did like, baby said and little stuff like that.

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:55.000
But my father was no. He did take my brothers out in painting houses with him.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:24:04.000
But they were working for him, not for that. And then that was like doing that summertime. But for the girls and that was four of us.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:15.000
And none of us were involved in doing that. It was one of the things that to make sure that he kept his family safe.

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:23.000
And my father had a real proudness about the fact that he felt that he was able to support his family.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:26.000
You know, he felt very, very good about that.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:32.000
Did you have a sense of him being protective at the time? Did you understand that?

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:38.000
I think I understood that more. I do remember when in Muteil was killed.

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:44.000
His actually body was brought into a funeral home there in Greenwood.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:50.000
And there was all the squirrsparing about what really happened to the boy and stuff.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:58.000
And my father was always very protective and always saying that if you don't do what he said, you things could happen.

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:04.000
And he wanted to make sure that nothing happened to any of his children.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:12.000
Did you see where you were? So the said, he said his body was in Greenwood?

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:18.000
Yeah, that was a whisper about that after the body was taken out.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:28.000
I remember my parents had said that he is that the funeral homes were all nervous about which one of them, none of them really wanted it.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:34.000
But because nobody wanted to get involved in what had happened.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:38.000
That was worried about what had happened.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:46.000
I mean, my mother had once talked about that she had heard when she was growing up about a person being burned alive.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:57.000
So all of these are gruesome tales and all of this that one is always cautious about what could really happen to you.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:05.000
So it was always being very, very careful that nothing was going to happen.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:11.000
There were Mississippi was considered to be a complete dry state when I was growing up.

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:18.000
And that was dry in terms of no liquor, no beer, no nothing.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:24.000
But people, there were people who sold liquor and stuff.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:38.000
And my father used to always say that one of the problems with the people who were bootlegging and all of that is that they basically had made a pack with the folks downtown.

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:52.000
So that he said that you know you have to be very careful about them is that they have to provide information so they can stay in business.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:59.000
So he said that sometimes if they don't have information they make up stuff on people.

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:07.000
So they would like that accommodation of those folks that it was just saying you got to watch out for.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:10.000
And you were just very, very careful.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:16.000
It was always the question of being careful about what you did and where you went.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:22.000
And that it would tell you if he was here you would say I know all the good people in town.

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:28.000
I know all the bad people do so that's the reason why.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:31.000
And that's the reason why you have to do that.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:43.000
I've been in Greenwood and it seems to me that Greenwood is the starkest any place I've ever been in terms of the contrast between the white part of town and the white part of town.

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:47.000
Did you ever have any reason to go in the white part of town?

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:48.000
Never.

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:55.000
I know how the difference was mainly because I had you know, you know I did have my tonsils removed.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:28:00.000
I mean the hospital was over in the white part of town.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:12.000
But now Greenwood not only in terms of that but Greenwood has the large Jewish community did and they had that little community where they lived.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:24.000
So the that you should say is the North Greenwood and North Greenwood was considered to be these were the old folks who probably traced their roots back to the plant.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:29.000
And these were people who really had money.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:39.000
Then there was the other the regular white folks who only thing they had going for themselves is that they were white and they went to the better schools and we did.

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:41.000
And then there was the Jewish community.

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:52.000
When I was growing up throughout the black community there were Chinese people and the Chinese people had these little small grocery stores.

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:56.000
But the Chinese people lived above their stores.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:29:03.000
Now their children went to the white school but they lived in the black community.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:08.000
So I know people that was over near the school where they lived.

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:13.000
They used to play with the Chinese kids in the neighborhoods.

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:19.000
Now there were no Chinese over here and I were in neighborhoods so I definitely never played with them.

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:31.000
A block from us was a little strip where about four different white families lived with children played but we never played with them.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:41.000
For people who don't who can't visualize it can you paint us a quick picture of what the differences between the different parts of town were.

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:52.000
I think that most of the black community were what we call shotgun houses.

00:29:52.000 --> 00:30:00.000
They were little and they were houses that were built also on, they sat like on pillows just about.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:12.000
A brick stack, a brick and three room houses one right behind the other one throughout the black community.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:20.000
Some places there were sidewalks, there were some places that were not sidewalks.

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:32.000
There was also throughout the black community. There were places where you were not sidewalks where you went across a plank which really means that you're really going across an open sewer.

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:40.000
And that's how people and that's probably how it was in the majority of the black community.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:49.000
Now as I said in the older part of the black community over in the area where I lived is that we're still talking about frame houses.

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:55.000
We're talking about I mean these are just older houses.

00:30:55.000 --> 00:31:04.000
I'm concerned that my mother was born in 1907 and her mother had been born in like 1874.

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:12.000
They had all lived in this house and over time the family had added more and more space onto it.

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:23.000
But my great grandmother had originally owned that land so it was like a little piece here and there.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:31.000
Now because we lived inside the city you were not allowed to raise chickens or anything like that.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:38.000
People did my grandmother had had a garden. My mother was not into garden and so she did not.

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:42.000
So when my grandmother was alive there were vegetables and stuff.

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:48.000
Otherwise we bought those from the farmers who came into town with that.

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:57.000
But in the white community you're talking about in North Green with this huge the anti-bellum houses.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:00.000
So they would divide growing on them.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:05.000
So some of those are really beautiful back in.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:07.000
No that's in the olden days.

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:14.000
Then in the regular white community there's still frame houses.

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:17.000
I mean brick houses are an inception to the rule.

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:21.000
I mean that's really when you're talking about this white.

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:31.000
Then right before, right in the early 60s they build up what they called a housing development.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:34.000
And there's people were coming back from the war.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:36.000
They were finally able to get.

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:43.000
Because I think part of the problem is that it was no way to get financing for a house.

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:46.000
So then these GI's were coming back.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:52.000
And they did build up this little development which was directly across the street from the high school.

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:56.000
But that was still you're talking about four room houses.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:32:59.000
You know a very small place.

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:08.000
But at least this was for the first time that people began to see an opportunity to be able to buy a place.

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:10.000
Or to have a more space.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:14.000
And I think that's the problem is it just happened decent housing.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:20.000
And rather than all of these families having to live in these three shotgun houses.

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:23.000
And I've heard it out.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:29.000
It's true that some of the shotgun houses will move from plantation.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:31.000
Yeah, I'm not sure.

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:32.000
I mean I'm not sure.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:40.000
But I mean you're talking about really, you're talking about frame houses and frame houses that over time,

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:45.000
if maintenance is not done and people don't own the houses.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:52.000
So you got the wood just deteriorates over time.

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:57.000
I mean that's part of the reason why they painted.

00:33:57.000 --> 00:34:00.000
No to protect the wood and stuff.

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:03.000
So you're talking about these frame houses as vending.

00:34:03.000 --> 00:34:06.000
You're also talking about large families that have to live there.

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:11.000
Because this is the only place that they actually have to live.

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:13.000
So it's kind of a rough.

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:14.000
Yeah.

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:19.000
What do you remember about how did you first encounter the movement?

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:24.000
Well, my father had been involved in the end of the ACP.

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:30.000
I mean my father and mother really had registered to vote in the late 50s,

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:33.000
even though they actually never voted.

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:35.000
They had registered to vote.

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:40.000
So my father had been involved often with the end of the ACP.

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:48.000
Then in 1962, they just mentioned that they had done it.

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:52.000
But people talked about registered and the vote.

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:54.000
This was whisper in kind of thing.

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:59.000
This was not something that you wanted to advertise because it was always...

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:04.000
My father definitely always let you know that you never knew who you were talking to.

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:09.000
And that some people would just call struggle, you know.

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:20.000
But in 1962, my brother, Dwight, had just returned from doing a tour in the Navy.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:24.000
And he applied and was going to, at that time,

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:27.000
he was Mississippi Vocational College.

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:31.000
And now it's Mississippi Valley State University.

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:34.000
In Itta Bena, Mississippi, he was going there.

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:37.000
But he wanted to go to Ole Miss.

00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:39.000
So he applied...

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:45.000
Well, in Mississippi, if you went to college the only thing you could take was education.

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:48.000
And he didn't want education.

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:51.000
So he wanted to find something else to do.

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:57.000
So he applied to be the second black student at Ole Miss.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:00.000
Now he did not get accepted.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:07.000
But that began to cause a lot of attention, more attention on my family.

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:09.000
So that he...

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:16.000
But that is said that he got a call from the mayor that come downtown.

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:20.000
They wanted to talk to him.

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:25.000
You know, come downtown as quick as you can.

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:31.000
So that is just said that he said, well, he wouldn't...

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:34.000
He'd come, just come home from work.

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:37.000
He said he figured he'd go down and see the man in the morgue.

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:39.000
He went down.

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:47.000
And he told him, your boy applied to go to Ole Miss.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:52.000
And we want you to tell him to take back his application.

00:36:53.000 --> 00:37:00.000
So that is said that he said he told him, well, you know, I can't tell him to take back his application.

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:05.000
He said, I didn't tell him to apply, but I won't tell him to take it back.

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:11.000
So he said that the mayor told him, well, you better think about it.

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:16.000
And so that is how that whole conversation ended.

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:18.000
So he didn't get in.

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:23.000
So then he went to work for the Mississippi Free Press,

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:29.000
which was a small little newspaper that was given out in Jackson.

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:37.000
So do we begin to meet other political active people, Robert Parris Moses and his SNCC cohort that was...

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:42.000
Because at that time, SNCC had people down in Southwest Mississippi.

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:45.000
And he also met Medgar Evers.

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:48.000
So Robert Parris Moses was putting that...

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:50.000
He met Robert Parris Moses.

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:52.000
He met Sam Block.

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:55.000
He met Willie Peacock, Reggie Robinson.

00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:58.000
All the people who were then down in the southern part of...

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:01.000
These are people down in the southern part.

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:04.000
He also met...

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:09.000
God, that...

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:13.000
I can't think of his name right now over in Cleveland,

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:16.000
who was Amzie Moore.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:17.000
Amzie Moore.

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:20.000
And Amzie Moore said, well, I mean, he was...

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:23.000
Because Amzie Moore was interested in the Free Press.

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:29.000
And he said, because the Free Press probably was the only kind of paper

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:33.000
that basically was given out factual information,

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:36.000
or what was really going on.

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:41.000
So he and Amzie Moore had cultivated this relationship.

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:45.000
He said, well, Amzie Moore said, I'll help distribute your paper

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:48.000
and you can help me get things in the paper.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:53.000
So it was like this was how things basically was done, you know.

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:55.000
Making things work.

00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:59.000
So all of this began to hit.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:05.000
And then Willie Peacock and Sam Block came into Greenwood that summer.

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:07.000
So this is like the summer.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:13.000
So we're into the fall of 62 and they're coming in and stuff.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:17.000
And I just began to go to Mass Meedens,

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:20.000
because as they began to have mass meetings,

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:23.000
now we talk about mass meetings all the time.

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:25.000
We do it.

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:29.000
We give a new definition to Mass.

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:33.000
You think about Mass as men as huge crowd.

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:37.000
Sometimes it may have been 20 people.

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:41.000
But we call them Mass Meedens.

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:47.000
A Mass meeting, there was the Hollis Watkins version that comes in with the singing

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:52.000
to arouse people, to try to encourage people to register the vote.

00:39:52.000 --> 00:40:00.000
So it's like, to start now with singing to now give some type of spiritual

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:04.000
uplifting and to encourage people to get people involved.

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:08.000
And then that's different speakers that from time to time.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:10.000
I mean, Medgar Evers with some Robert Parris Moses and all of this,

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:15.000
all to talk to people about trying to get folks to register the vote.

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:17.000
So we're going to all of these.

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:20.000
I'm going my brother George,

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:23.000
who's like 18 months older than me.

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:25.000
And George is like really going.

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:29.000
So we are all involved in trying to do this.

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:32.000
This is that whole...

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:34.000
My father did.

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:37.000
My mother was not very much involved.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:40.000
She did not go, but my father did.

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:43.000
And we go to all of this now.

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:48.000
At this time, Mississippi in Leflore County, Mississippi,

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:52.000
surplus food is being distributed to people.

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:57.000
People are really having a hard time surviving.

00:40:57.000 --> 00:41:00.000
Because Mississippi, in the Delta area,

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:03.000
so many of the people had lived out,

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:05.000
have been cotton pickers.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:12.000
And in 62 was probably the first time they began to introduce the cotton pickers

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:18.000
into the, no, the electric machines to pick the cotton.

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:22.000
So the people then are not making much money,

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:26.000
because they're picking up after the pickers have come through the machines.

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:31.000
And it's a very hot winner for them.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:32.000
It's cold.

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:34.000
They haven't made much money.

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:36.000
And people are trying to survive.

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:39.000
So they really do need the surplus food.

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:41.000
And we're not talking about luxury.

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:43.000
We're talking about powdered milk.

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:44.000
No.

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:47.000
Some teas, products, peanut butter.

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:49.000
And so it's little leads.

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:53.000
But this is what people needed to survive.

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:58.000
So that in Leflore County, Mississippi, they discontinued the food.

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:01.000
It's surplus food to all these people.

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:05.000
And this is as result of people getting involved in the movement.

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:08.000
So that made it extremely difficult.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:13.000
So as results, throughout the North and Dick Gregory,

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:18.000
rented a plane and brought down surplus, brought down food down.

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:23.000
And the food was distributed from Wesley,

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:26.000
Methodist Church, which is two blocks from where I lived.

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:28.000
And I met my church.

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:31.000
And we helped with the distributed food.

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:34.000
Because I'm too young to register the vote.

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:37.000
I can do, and this is one of the things I can do.

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:41.000
And that's when it became very clear.

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:43.000
And my dad had what Stephanie is saying.

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:47.000
He said, they are trying their best to stop these people to death.

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:50.000
Because it's all they have.

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:53.000
It's this little dried milk and peanut butter.

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:58.000
And they are discontinuing the commodities for the people.

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:01.000
So on the one hand, there's less need for labor.

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:04.000
And on the other hand, people are trying to register the vote.

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:05.000
Right.

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:08.000
And as a result, Mississippi says,

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:12.000
we are going to do everything we can to stop you from doing this.

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:15.000
What was it like for you, you're a high school student.

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:18.000
And did you have a big Gregory Charter in a plane?

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:22.000
Well, I mean, that was like...

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:26.000
I was not that familiar with who Dick Gregory was.

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:30.000
I mean, he was now, wasn't in Tateena.

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:32.000
But I was not.

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:36.000
But it was a real big surprise.

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:43.000
And it was a welcome idea that somebody really did care about these people.

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:49.000
So it was a big effort when he brought into plane and brought in food and stuff.

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:58.000
And then even when Ivanhoe Donaldson, the son was driving down a truckload of food from the north.

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:05.000
That was also the idea that people really was trying their best to help.

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:06.000
Yeah.

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:09.000
So what was your job at the church?

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:11.000
To help distribute the food.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:19.000
We would divide the stuff, bagging, boxing up things, helping distribute it to families.

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:25.000
So what do you remember about the SNCC workers coming into town?

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:27.000
What was your impression of it?

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:30.000
Well, I felt very good.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:36.000
Because it was like, one, it was people who always talk to you about different things.

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:46.000
And it was like, Stokely Carmichael would tell me about growing up in New York and about his family being from Trinidad.

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:50.000
So it was like, it was a lot of information.

00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:59.000
It was, it was an exposure to something else other than Mississippi as it was.

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:03.000
And people used to watch the soap operas, no, on television.

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:10.000
And it's just like, all of a sudden it was very clear to me that that was an outside world.

00:45:10.000 --> 00:45:17.000
That you could see other than things that you read about in the books.

00:45:17.000 --> 00:45:21.000
Because growing up, it was nothing to do.

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:27.000
And so the library used to be, the public library was not open to us.

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:35.000
What the used to do is that at the junior high school they would open up that library two days during the week.

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:38.000
So at least you could go and check out books.

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:41.000
But there was no summer programs.

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:43.000
There was nothing to do.

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:47.000
So as a high school person growing up, there was nothing.

00:45:47.000 --> 00:45:53.000
So now all of a sudden I have all of these people who are coming down, who are college students,

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:58.000
and they are going to all of the schools who have just heard about.

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:03.000
I mean Harvard, Yale, I mean this is the Howard.

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:07.000
And I had never known anybody to go to all of this.

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:14.000
So I just feel that it is so much information out there.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:18.000
And my father is encouraging me to do it.

00:46:18.000 --> 00:46:23.000
Now I can remember I was a senior in high school and I met Eleanor Holmes,

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:26.000
who was in law school.

00:46:26.000 --> 00:46:29.000
And it would be interesting to what was possible.

00:46:29.000 --> 00:46:34.000
Well it definitely made it very clear there was a lot of things that was possible.

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:36.000
I mean she was going to Yale.

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:41.000
I mean it was, Tim Jenkins.

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:45.000
I met all of these when I was in high school.

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:55.000
And it just gave me, and people talked to you about other things that was going on.

00:46:55.000 --> 00:47:01.000
Who are some of those people locally in your community who are leaders?

00:47:01.000 --> 00:47:13.000
Well I guess when you talk about leaders, I guess most people think about the teachers as been.

00:47:13.000 --> 00:47:16.000
And none of the teachers were involved in the Civil Rights Movement.

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:19.000
They were not.

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:28.000
And I think most of it was people were terrified of losing their jobs.

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:33.000
June Johnson's mother was, June Johnson's mother was involved in the movement.

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:37.000
The McGee family who owned a farm.

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:41.000
They didn't live directly in Greenwood but only outside of Greenwood.

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:44.000
They were very involved in the movement.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:50.000
Reverend Johnson who had owned a, they had this little church.

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:55.000
And his church was called the First Christian Church.

00:47:55.000 --> 00:48:02.000
Up until he had the, and he had the first mass meeting with Heldeth his church.

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:10.000
Then the wife folks said that he could not be the First Christian Church because they had the First Christian Church downtown.

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:15.000
And he had had this church as the First Christian Church for years.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:18.000
But then the wife people said no, you can't.

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:20.000
So he had to change the name of the church.

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:23.000
And I can't think of now what the name of his church is.

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:30.000
But his church had to be, even though clearly there was, everyone would know that which was which.

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:33.000
But they, but he had to change the name.

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:36.000
And he was a, he's Aaron Johnson.

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:42.000
He was a big activist in the Hobick movement.

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:50.000
Tucker, Sterling Tucker was also, was another minister that was involved.

00:48:50.000 --> 00:48:55.000
And you see, you had ministers who would get out and do things.

00:48:55.000 --> 00:49:02.000
You had the McGee family, you had the Johnson's, and you had us, the Greens, and you printed my tummy.

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:05.000
People were afraid.

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:12.000
I mean, people, I mean, that, it became very, very clear to me that people were definitely very much afraid.

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:18.000
And they were afraid that you were going to make something happen to them.

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:19.000
You know.

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:21.000
So the people started avoiding?

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:25.000
People, they just, they want to be involved in the movement.

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:31.000
You know, I mean, so it was clear lines between people who were movement,

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:34.000
who were involved, and people were not.

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:44.000
And doing march of, March 1963, after my brother George had attended a meeting over at the SNCC office,

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:51.000
it's when he came home, somebody evidently had followed the car that dropped him off,

00:49:51.000 --> 00:50:00.000
and they, somebody came by and blasted the house with shotgun, you know, through the front door and through the front bedroom.

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:08.000
So that, this, this was all the scary tactics that was happening to people, you know.

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:10.000
Did you have to obey?

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:19.000
No. I mean, if anything, my father said that this is more, this is a clear indication that we have to do something.

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:28.000
Because they're doing things to us, no matter whether we do something or not, and we have to change the way things are.

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:36.000
However, for some of the people who I knew at school, they did not, their parents didn't want them involved with us,

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:39.000
because they were afraid that we were going to get them in trouble.

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:45.000
You know, I mean, people, I mean, and that was the whole fear, is that you were going to get me in trouble, you know.

00:50:45.000 --> 00:50:53.000
And, and it was my senior year in high school, and people applying for the schools, and they're trying to, you know, get scholarships,

00:50:53.000 --> 00:51:02.000
and they don't want you to do anything that they feel that may jeopardize their chance for something to happen.

00:51:02.000 --> 00:51:04.000
But you felt confident.

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:14.000
Well, I did. I mean, as far as I'm concerned, my parents were, my father was definitely very, very supportive of us being involved in the movement and stuff.

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:27.000
And, and I went on that September to Dillard University in New Orleans. I mean, I, but it was like, I wanted to do, I did not want to go to school in Mississippi.

00:51:27.000 --> 00:51:31.000
I wanted to, I wanted to go somewhere to see something.

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:37.000
So, and I was also at that time interested in nursing, and Dillard had a nursing program.

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:46.000
So, and it was the first time I'd ever been to Dillard with when I took the train.

00:51:46.000 --> 00:51:56.000
My folks carried me to Winona, which was 25 miles away, and took the train down, and went to school.

00:51:56.000 --> 00:51:59.000
That's how you got to know Dillard.

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:03.000
That's how I got to know Dillard. So, it was no college visits.

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:06.000
Yeah.

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:15.000
Did you, were you around when they had the festival album, this is the movies, far with different singers?

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:21.000
Oh, yes indeed. There's no question about it. It is Pete Seeger and all of that.

00:52:21.000 --> 00:52:26.000
You know, Pete Seeger came down, Pete Seeger and all of that.

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:30.000
And then the papers talked about him all, it's being commoners.

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:37.000
Dad said, that's the, he said, you know, they talk about everybody who want to do something to help the black folks.

00:52:37.000 --> 00:52:41.000
So, it was like, I mean, that was a big concern.

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:55.000
And I think that it was one of the kinds of things that helped people like me see that there were other people who definitely thought that you deserved an opportunity to be able to do something.

00:52:55.000 --> 00:53:00.000
So, you remember the day and you remember being out on the farm?

00:53:00.000 --> 00:53:07.000
I remember being out on the farm. I remember hearing Pete Seeger and, you know, and...

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:10.000
The Freedom Singers perform?

00:53:10.000 --> 00:53:11.000
Yeah.

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:20.000
Yeah. Oh, yeah. Oh, no, no. That was a big, big cultural enrichment for the black community.

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:39.000
And I think it was those kinds of things. It was also as the free Southern theater began to travel throughout Mississippi and do plays that it became very clear that you could have...

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:52.000
You could get a chance to see other kinds of activities, you know, and if you would not just regulate it to a segregated school with no opportunity to do something.

00:53:52.000 --> 00:53:58.000
And Pete, that's what's the encouragement to do something else, you know.

00:53:58.000 --> 00:54:15.000
I mean, I honestly think that I think that teachers in school always... I mean, they taught the schoolwork, that's all, but it was clearly a line that they didn't talk about doing other things, you know.

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:20.000
I mean, they're exposure, and then I guess part of it was because most of the...

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:33.000
All of them had either gone to Jackson State or they had gone to Alabama State. I mean, these were all teachers and education was the only thing that they knew and they didn't think about how things could be.

00:54:33.000 --> 00:54:39.000
What was it like for you to be so involved in the movement and then lead to go to college?

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:49.000
I mean, that was very hard. It was very hard because when it was time for me to go to college, we had just had some big demonstrations in Greenwood.

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:58.000
And they had arrested my brother George and they had made off a card, none of that, and then Hollis. And it was a big group of them that were down in Parchman Farm.

00:54:58.000 --> 00:55:13.000
They had sent them down to Parchman Farm because they arrested them and they had to try to transfer them down to Parchman Farm, probably within a day of that whole big process.

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:15.000
What was it being charged with?

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:19.000
Trust passed and was always, you know.

00:55:20.000 --> 00:55:29.000
Since we lived so close to Greenwood to downtown, when they actually brought in the...

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:33.000
Had the police dogs, we could hear the dogs barking at my house.

00:55:33.000 --> 00:55:45.000
Yeah, I mean, the dogs are like going to town. The dogs are barking and they had sick the dogs on the people for the marches and all.

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:52.000
They're arrested to group of people, sent them down to Parchman Farm and now it's time for me to go away to college.

00:55:52.000 --> 00:55:55.000
And my brother is in Parchman Farm, so.

00:55:55.000 --> 00:56:02.000
School together, right? Yeah. Yeah, so we've gone to school together. So I was really concerned.

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:11.000
I remembered talking to my daddy about that being very concerned and I remember talking with James Forman.

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:18.000
James Forman was a good mentor for me and I really did like him very much.

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:29.000
And I remember saying to Jim saying, well, don't worry, we're going to look out for George (her brother George) for you, but you go on and get your school and he said,

00:56:29.000 --> 00:56:34.000
because this is going to help you and you're going to be able to do so much more when you come back.

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:46.000
So I went on off to Dillard University for my freshman year and I was there. I was at Dillard University when they bombed the church in Alabama.

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:57.000
No, the girls would kill. So I mean, that was like really very, very shocking because it was like, it seemed as if that nothing was ever going to stop.

00:56:57.000 --> 00:57:03.000
And that they've been all of this. This is also after the time, Medgar Evers have been killed.

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:14.000
You know, they've been the gunshots in my house. It just seems as if so it's very hard studying and stuff and being separated from all that was going on.

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:21.000
Because at Dillard University, nobody was concerned. Nobody was interested in a movement.

00:57:21.000 --> 00:57:32.000
I mean, they did not have any student group at all. Now, I did make connections with Tulane.

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:41.000
I, Cathy Cade (likely) or Casey Hayden was over in Tulane in the Newman Center.

00:57:41.000 --> 00:57:43.000
She had been in Albany?

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:56.000
Yeah, she had been, she had been somewhere in Southwest Georgia. But I can't remember. She had been somewhere because she, someone had given her my name and told her I was at Dillard University.

00:57:56.000 --> 00:58:06.000
And she came over because during the time when I was at Dillard University, girls were, rules and regulations for girls in schools was extremely strict.

00:58:06.000 --> 00:58:18.000
It was harder. My rules were tighter than my mom and dad had ever had. So, Kathy could come over to visit me. But I couldn't go to visit her.

00:58:18.000 --> 00:58:27.000
So I went to visit her and then I had to get parents permission for her to be able to take me, for me to ride in a car, to go to Tulane.

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:37.000
Because Tulane did have some student group. They wasn't that active, but they were, they were, they were, they were at least a group.

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:48.000
Since Dillard University had nothing. So I got involved. I went over to see them after I got my parents permission, a letter from my parents and all of that, given them.

00:58:48.000 --> 00:59:00.000
And you got to send all of this by mail because we don't have this fast letters of communication. So that was very interesting.

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:15.000
Interesting times just being there. So then I find out for my brother George that there's going to be this big summer project that summer of 64.

00:59:15.000 --> 00:59:23.000
And so I of course I'm all interested in doing that. But since I've been away from home, I don't want to go back to Greenwood.

00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:41.000
I want to go somewhere. So George tells me that he's going to be working in a project in McComb, Mississippi, Mississippi. And he said, you know, I'll talk to dad and let's see about where it's going to be okay for you to come to McComb, Mississippi.

00:59:42.000 --> 00:59:52.000
So I go and I, I, I, I, George helped me get that in my mom to agree for me to like go and work in McComb, Mississippi doing the summer of 64.

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:57.000
But prior to the summer of 64, I went to the orientation up in Ohio.

00:59:57.000 --> 01:00:00.000
So was your brother to get more freedom than you did?

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:07.000
Oh, yeah. I mean, it's no question about just partially because one he was older partially because he was a boy.

01:00:07.000 --> 01:00:17.000
I mean, so it's no question about is they were much, much more rules were much more strict on girls than we're on boys and stuff.

01:00:17.000 --> 01:00:22.000
So like George could drive. Actually, George taught me to drive.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:29.000
My father had taught my oldest two brothers to drive and when George was a little boy, because he was younger than them.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:38.000
He used to, when daddy would go to sleep, he was still the car that teached and so George technically told himself to drive.

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:49.000
But he was, he was determined to drive. So he learned to drive and then he taught me to drive.

01:00:49.000 --> 01:00:56.000
So, but George, George was a big car person, loved to drive all around.

01:00:56.000 --> 01:01:07.000
So he convinced me to come to McComb, Mississippi. I went to McComb, Mississippi, went to the orientation up in Ohio. Then we came back to McComb, Mississippi.

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:23.000
But I was here in Washington because the group that was going to go to McComb, Mississippi came from Ohio over to Washington to meet with the try to see the volunteers.

01:01:23.000 --> 01:01:38.000
So they came with the volunteers over here to try to meet with their congressional representatives to ask for additional protection for them while we were in Mississippi during the summer project.

01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:44.000
So, what, that partially the group that was going to be in Southwest Mississippi because they figured Southwest was going to be worse.

01:01:44.000 --> 01:01:55.000
So we came in to discuss with Congress people the representatives for the volunteers who was going on that project.

01:01:55.000 --> 01:02:09.000
We were here when the word came to Ohio that Schwerner, Chaney, and Goodman and, and Goodman had been kidnapped.

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:17.000
So then we got that message and we went immediately back to, to Ohio for that.

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:24.000
Now there's no question about it is when I arrived in Ohio, it was very clear. Everybody felt that the people were dead.

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:39.000
So I think that among the staff, the SNCC staff and the, the, the whole summer project staff, they definitely felt that they were dead.

01:02:39.000 --> 01:02:46.000
And then the question was what, what Mississippi or what the FBI in the Bay was going to do anything about it.

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:55.000
So that group organized a search group that then went into Mississippi to try to look for it.

01:02:55.000 --> 01:03:03.000
But then I'm sure you recognize that whole story of what happened.

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:05.000
But I went on to McComb.

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:17.000
And I would, we worked, we divided up the, the, the work in McComb that was the freedom schools, that was the people who canvass to try to get it.

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:27.000
We also took terms with cleaning up the house. We had this one freedom house that all of 11 of us that was staying there.

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:37.000
In that process, our house, we used to take terms, supposedly, staying awake to God to protect everybody else.

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:53.000
Unfortunately, the night, that, the night before that happened, we had had this big staff meeting there at the house trying to decide whether it was time for the other volunteers to come down there.

01:03:53.000 --> 01:03:57.000
Because we had been down there for, for two weeks and we needed help.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:01.000
And whether, what, why they were in the way for the other volunteers.

01:04:01.000 --> 01:04:05.000
Well, they wanted to make sure that it was safe.

01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:13.000
And, and so first we just carried in half the volunteers went into that group, into that.

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:18.000
Because McComb was considered to be a hotbed. So whether it was going to be safe.

01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:27.000
We went down for two weeks, worked hard and they just felt that, that it, things had gone very well.

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:39.000
They had, we had a big staff meeting there at the house. Everybody voted, everybody voted for the other volunteers to come, except my brother George, who felt they was not, he said.

01:04:39.000 --> 01:04:47.000
I don't want to be responsible for somebody getting hurt. So we bring down more people, it's going to be more responsible.

01:04:47.000 --> 01:04:55.000
But since we voted for it, he was outvoted, that night the house was bombed.

01:04:55.000 --> 01:05:08.000
So the, they have, basically somebody really walked up to the garage door and put down a couple sticks. So, dynamite.

01:05:08.000 --> 01:05:18.000
Now, it took out the garage door, it shattered windows and houses for people from two blocks away.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:31.000
And no one would seriously hurt, courageous haze, who would sleep and very close to the door, head like fragments of glass that was really implanted in him.

01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:53.000
Nobody really got seriously hurt. My brother George, the next death that morning after we, after that whole bombing drove, heard his back up to Jackson, so that he could be a Xamarin by the doctor so we can make sure that nothing really had gone, that no one was really hurt.

01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:56.000
What was your life to be in that situation?

01:05:56.000 --> 01:06:09.000
Now, you know, I heard this loud explosion and I was asleep. And, but I woke me up and I instantly, I thought they were out there playing.

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:21.000
I couldn't understand. And it was like, I came out of the room and somebody yelled, get down, get down. And then it turns out, I mean, it was like all of a sudden.

01:06:21.000 --> 01:06:30.000
And then it was like, we were, the other guys were on the floor and it was like, you know, something has happened.

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:39.000
And it was like, all of a sudden we were crawling toward the garage and you can see that the half of the house has been taken away, whether it's been really bombed.

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:44.000
Now, that was really very frightening.

01:06:44.000 --> 01:07:01.000
And we, the police came and they, they pretended like they didn't understand what had happened, you know, and say, what did y'all do, you know, to this house, you know, so it's, it's like, it's a strange kind of thing.

01:07:02.000 --> 01:07:12.000
The call is made to Jackson and also to Greenwood, which is where the National Office for Snick was the summer of 6th of 4.

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:27.000
They temporarily moved the National Office to Greenwood, so they relayed over what had happened down there. And George is going to take Curtis into Jackson as soon as they like comes in to see the doctor.

01:07:28.000 --> 01:07:43.000
And the next day as you're walking around, we decided that we have to, the keep the community calm, we have to go on as a normal day in campus and in and off.

01:07:43.000 --> 01:07:57.000
But as you are walking down the street, it's very clear, people are closing their doors when they say, they're just, I mean, they're just, and this is all the fear that people are really very, very much afraid.

01:07:57.000 --> 01:08:12.000
So they are just a very afraid that's, that's something is going to happen, you know. And we are trying our best to act as normal and to keep things going as normally as possible.

01:08:12.000 --> 01:08:20.000
Were there any lights in the cone to spoke out against the violence or anything?

01:08:20.000 --> 01:08:38.000
Not really. What there was, and I can't think of the family doing the, yes. This is the relationship, because that's how the story and what actually happened is slightly different.

01:08:38.000 --> 01:08:53.000
There was a minister from Oregon who had known him while they were in the military. And they were, the chaplains, the chaplains, yeah.

01:08:53.000 --> 01:09:08.000
He had known that they have not done the military and they over time had, the families had just changed Christmas cards back with some force. And then when he came there, he wanted to go and visit him.

01:09:08.000 --> 01:09:14.000
Because this is somebody that, that he known for the military and he wanted to go and visit.

01:09:14.000 --> 01:09:24.000
This is one of the volunteers. He's a minister. He wants to go and visit and we all have this discussion about whether this visit should take place.

01:09:24.000 --> 01:09:35.000
But then they decided that he could go, but he was also going to take with him one of the other volunteers that were there. And we picked out the one guy that he was going to take.

01:09:35.000 --> 01:09:51.000
Dennis Sweeney, who was a Stanford student, white, blonde, blue eyes. And it's like the two of them could very easily pass off as father and son, father and uncle.

01:09:51.000 --> 01:10:12.000
And they would not be noticeable. They would go and visit. So technically they went to Vicks, the Heffners. Now, as the Heffners now tell the story that they made the overture, but it actually happened the other way around.

01:10:12.000 --> 01:10:36.000
And then the minister went in to visit them. And I mean, actually, of course he's shocked to see him standing on his doorstep. But the Heffners were, what's considered to be a freedom, I mean, their daughter had been, they run up to Mississippi.

01:10:36.000 --> 01:10:53.000
And they knew that they were a respected family. They own the hardware store in downtown. But as a result of this visit from then that point on, the white folks there gave them a complete hard time and they in return left.

01:10:53.000 --> 01:10:57.000
But there was none that came out to our support.

01:10:57.000 --> 01:11:02.000
So nobody's saying anything in the face of even the house being bombed.

01:11:02.000 --> 01:11:11.000
Even that the house being bombed. No, no one is saying anything. The house is bombed and are all around the county.

01:11:11.000 --> 01:11:21.000
There were, I think nine different churches that were set afi a black church that was set afi and nobody is saying anything.

01:11:21.000 --> 01:11:39.000
It was extremely hard because it's like people, you are one you could die. Secondly is that you could definitely lose what little you have, you know, people are all just very much afraid.

01:11:39.000 --> 01:11:43.000
So it's, it's, you are definitely putting your life on the line.

01:11:43.000 --> 01:11:47.000
Were you involved in organizing the MFP?

01:11:47.000 --> 01:12:07.000
Well, that's basically what we are doing. We are canvassing, getting people, we're going to setting up little meetings to vote for our delegates and all of that. And that's basically what we, what that's the project that I'm working on because some people are dealing with the freedom schools that was that was going on.

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:24.000
And it was a very short summer. So we are trying to get that organized and we get our delegates selected and then I go up with them to Atlantic City for the convention, the democratic convention.

01:12:24.000 --> 01:12:38.000
I mean, that was definitely a mind blowing event because one is it's something that I had never considered that was possible that we could go.

01:12:38.000 --> 01:12:57.000
And my father said to he died and he said, I don't care whether they see the does or not. We showed everybody that it was possible for us to go and we could present our case for the whole country to see.

01:12:57.000 --> 01:13:12.000
And then I think that that that was probably one of the biggest things that people really did feel that now at least it's open up and so when Miss Hamer is making her speech that becomes world wide and the people.

01:13:12.000 --> 01:13:17.000
It's like all of a sudden people know what they are doing to us.

01:13:17.000 --> 01:13:26.000
You know, and now they have to make that decision about which side they are really on.

01:13:26.000 --> 01:13:31.000
Were you disappointed at the compromise that was offered?

01:13:31.000 --> 01:13:46.000
Well, I must admit is I really thought we were going to win. I thought I honestly felt that the delegates were going to say yes, you are all the legitimate group.

01:13:46.000 --> 01:14:01.000
You should have the seat. You know, but I think that what it did it exposed me to family that I just thought it was just Mississippi the tree that does like that.

01:14:01.000 --> 01:14:09.000
Not realize that Mississippi was able to do that because the rest of the country didn't care.

01:14:09.000 --> 01:14:17.000
But that's when it really became very, very clear. There wasn't just bad white folks in Mississippi.

01:14:17.000 --> 01:14:30.000
There were a lot of these people and that bad white folks in Mississippi had been able to do all of this to all of us down in Mississippi because the rest of the people did not care.

01:14:30.000 --> 01:14:37.000
Well, after that summer, I went back to Dilup for my second year and that was the hardest year.

01:14:37.000 --> 01:14:51.000
I mean, it was just very hard. I mean, it was very hard because I definitely felt that we needed to do something to make changes.

01:14:51.000 --> 01:15:03.000
And I felt that we needed to make changes. And everybody that was going to school with kept saying, well, you know, you finished school, you get yourself a good job and you can have a good life.

01:15:03.000 --> 01:15:16.000
And it's just, I just didn't feel that that's, I mean, it just seemed to me that I felt that there was basic changes in this country that we needed to make and we needed to have.

01:15:16.000 --> 01:15:28.000
And I needed to do things. I mean, I could not just keep studying and stuff and then just keep hoping and keep saying that I'll get a job and I will fix it.

01:15:28.000 --> 01:15:37.000
And I will be successful, you know, and the world will go on. And people kept saying, well, folks are doing bad because they don't have an education.

01:15:37.000 --> 01:15:49.000
You know, and we were like, they don't have an education because the system that we live on is so structured that people can't get an education and you can't have a good life.

01:15:49.000 --> 01:15:57.000
Well, when you, after that summer in McComb, Mississippi that fall, wasn't there just like bombing after that?

01:15:57.000 --> 01:16:09.000
That was. I mean, it was not only in McComb, Mississippi, but it was like everywhere and it was like, and it could get to be very interesting.

01:16:09.000 --> 01:16:16.000
You could have one conversation with somebody, they said, well, you know, these people, what, what causes trouble things wouldn't be having them.

01:16:16.000 --> 01:16:22.000
You said, well, we have to make changes.

01:16:22.000 --> 01:16:25.000
So you're the, you're the girl?

01:16:25.000 --> 01:16:37.000
Yeah, well, it was like, that's where the question gets to be. Some people would say that if we just set back things are going to change, things are going to get better.

01:16:37.000 --> 01:16:50.000
And you just said, well, things will not change on that. People just don't, they just don't just decide one day we're going to build good schools, good hospitals for everybody.

01:16:50.000 --> 01:16:53.000
And everybody's going to have an opportunity.

01:16:53.000 --> 01:16:59.000
So to make this happen, people have to do the active.

01:16:59.000 --> 01:17:08.000
And so at the end of my second year, I knew I couldn't go back. One is I didn't want nursing in the longer.

01:17:08.000 --> 01:17:19.000
And I couldn't go back to Dillard anyway, because I just, I could not stand the idea that all I need to do was get myself a good education, get a good job, and have a good life.

01:17:19.000 --> 01:17:32.000
And I wanted basically the system to change. And I wanted for it to be decent houses, decent places for everyone to live, and opportunities for people.

01:17:32.000 --> 01:17:39.000
And it had to be more than just education. I mean, it had to be. So, I mean, it's healthcare.

01:17:39.000 --> 01:17:47.000
And healthcare conditions in Mississippi was very, was deplorable. People never went to the doctors and stuff.

01:17:47.000 --> 01:17:59.000
I think if it wasn't for the, the shots that were given in the school systems, the vaccinations and all of that, people wouldn't have had anything.

01:17:59.000 --> 01:18:07.000
Because of public health, they at least gave you vaccinations in schools. Yeah.

01:18:07.000 --> 01:18:10.000
What did you do when you left Dillard?

01:18:10.000 --> 01:18:22.000
I left Dillard and I went, went back to work in, worked in Jackson on a voter registration. And we, to some of six to five, there was massive demonstrations in Jackson.

01:18:22.000 --> 01:18:30.000
And I was involved in all of those demonstrations. What they did in Jackson is they sent the black people to the fairground.

01:18:30.000 --> 01:18:42.000
They set the fairground up as a penitentiary. So, I spent a week there in the fairground, the penitentiary, and they put the white women that were arrested in the actual jail.

01:18:42.000 --> 01:18:48.000
What was it like in this kind of week at the fairground in the jail?

01:18:48.000 --> 01:18:58.000
Well, the first thing is the fairground. You're sleeping on a concrete floor and they basically give you a blanket at night.

01:18:58.000 --> 01:19:06.000
At nine o'clock every night they give you these blankets. But we're, I mean, it's a huge tent at the fairground.

01:19:06.000 --> 01:19:15.000
And the tent is constructed over this concrete floor. So you're sleeping on a desk. So it's no picnic.

01:19:15.000 --> 01:19:34.000
And basically the way the food is that it is a tray, a 10 tray that you get. And your breakfast is syrup or slice of light bread.

01:19:34.000 --> 01:19:47.000
And you're going through and then you're getting your food. Then after you eat, you go then and dip your tray into this hot thing of water.

01:19:47.000 --> 01:20:00.000
And that's how it's washed and it's stacked on and you're doing this. And it's like a couple hundred people. So this is like a line of people going through there.

01:20:00.000 --> 01:20:08.000
For lunch you get some type of grits. And for this the same process is same 10 tray that you're going through doing.

01:20:08.000 --> 01:20:23.000
And it's, you know, it's a very harsh condition, you know, on the fairground. And by the time I went in, people had been there for a couple of weeks and people were getting very upset.

01:20:23.000 --> 01:20:30.000
Because this is the pressing condition and nobody really knows when they're going to come out.

01:20:30.000 --> 01:20:38.000
So part of the process of the later photo in like me is to try to help lift up the morale.

01:20:38.000 --> 01:20:40.000
Going on the potential?

01:20:40.000 --> 01:20:51.000
Yeah, just to encourage people to stay on because we don't know. For that present time they're trying to raise money to get all these people out of jail and you have no idea.

01:20:51.000 --> 01:21:04.000
So you're really trying your best to encourage people. You know, trying as much as possible the most of the Janet Moses and I went in at the same time.

01:21:04.000 --> 01:21:18.000
It's hard. No, I mean you can understand the reluctance. But there's nothing that you can do. So you're getting you up at six o'clock and you're going to bed at nine.

01:21:18.000 --> 01:21:27.000
We're going to bed. You're laying on this concrete, you know, with a blanket so that a mat and sleep in on a concrete.

01:21:27.000 --> 01:21:30.000
What's the issue?

01:21:30.000 --> 01:21:40.000
I mean, it still is a question in terms of registered and devolved. I mean, this is still I mean, the summer 65 is before the civil rights, the civil rights bill.

01:21:40.000 --> 01:21:44.000
I believe it's signed that fall.

01:21:44.000 --> 01:21:49.000
Yeah, it's all got said. Well, this is all right prior to that. Yeah, to that.

01:21:49.000 --> 01:21:53.000
I mean, I know that there were huge arrests and a huge arrest.

01:21:53.000 --> 01:21:58.000
Yeah, and the fairground was the.

01:21:58.000 --> 01:22:05.000
When I got back out of jail, I went that's when I actually moved over to Atlanta.

01:22:05.000 --> 01:22:19.000
I went to work in the Atlanta Snick office. Now originally started out. I mean, and Jim form was also part of my motivation for going to gym and was trying his best to keep.

01:22:19.000 --> 01:22:26.000
He was the executive secretary of Snick and he was he would gym was a organizational person.

01:22:26.000 --> 01:22:37.000
So he was always trying to mix the groups of people and so he encouraged me to come to work in Atlanta office to and I worked on the switchboard.

01:22:37.000 --> 01:22:46.000
You want people who have been in the field to work in the office some and some of the people who are in the office to work in the field, you know.

01:22:46.000 --> 01:22:55.000
So you put people to understand the organization. I think it was a way it was also a way to do that.

01:22:55.000 --> 01:23:00.000
And it helped you to understand what was going on in the organization.

01:23:00.000 --> 01:23:12.000
And for all of us who had been in the field since sometimes they had been complaints that you didn't feel that other people were as understanding as they may have been.

01:23:12.000 --> 01:23:22.000
Having people from that helps with that because also you get to know each other and you can discuss it's different issues and all.

01:23:22.000 --> 01:23:29.000
So the standout team, you organization in general, or from your time in the office?

01:23:29.000 --> 01:23:38.000
Well, I went to work at the switchboard but I also was working very closely with Ruby Doris Smith Robinson.

01:23:38.000 --> 01:23:46.000
Now Rubidorus was also just like, in a lot of ways she was like Jim. She was like a woman, had graduated from Spelman.

01:23:46.000 --> 01:23:57.000
She had also been a Freedom Rider and stuff. And she had also been one of my heroes because I had met her at a Snick conference once before.

01:23:57.000 --> 01:24:06.000
And you know, she was a few years older than me. She had graduated from college and Rubid just seemed to have done everything.

01:24:06.000 --> 01:24:14.000
But she was also an organizational person. Rubid also would say that nobody couldn't have worked her.

01:24:14.000 --> 01:24:21.000
They couldn't out drive her. She was, no, she was just, in everything that she did she was just terrific.

01:24:21.000 --> 01:24:32.000
She always encouraged you to do just as much. So it was like she was always telling me that Freddie, what you want to do is learn as much stuff,

01:24:32.000 --> 01:24:39.000
as much different things as you can. So you can always decide upon what you really like.

01:24:39.000 --> 01:24:48.000
Most people say, because they've only done one thing in life and they just say, this is me. This is the kind of thing.

01:24:48.000 --> 01:24:57.000
She said, but you know, that's because they never saw anything and never did anything else. So you tried doing all these different kinds of things.

01:24:57.000 --> 01:25:07.000
And she was one of the people who got me involved in finance. Growing up in Mississippi, I would never find a suit, find an ass.

01:25:07.000 --> 01:25:17.000
And I was like, I'm not doing a business career. I'm understanding how offices function, how to count in and all of this.

01:25:17.000 --> 01:25:26.000
But this was all far and this is all results of Ruby and Jim basically encouraging me to do different things.

01:25:26.000 --> 01:25:33.000
And also they're always encouraging you to read things and telling you about something.

01:25:33.000 --> 01:25:39.000
So you move on to the Atlanta office. Does your brother George, does he continue organizing in the field?

01:25:39.000 --> 01:25:47.000
George stays in the field. He goes from Mississippi into George and into Alabama.

01:25:47.000 --> 01:25:55.000
Because doing 65 as Nick begins to set up more projects, you know, the Lowndes County, Alabama County Project, the Greene County, Alabama Project.

01:25:55.000 --> 01:26:04.000
George is working in Lions County. He's a field person. He would have never made it in an office.

01:26:04.000 --> 01:26:14.000
He just, in terms of personnel, he's just like going more, going in the field. He's like going out, canvassing, talking to the people and stuff.

01:26:14.000 --> 01:26:17.000
You know, he liked that a lot more.

01:26:17.000 --> 01:26:22.000
Who else were you working with in the Atlanta office? What are some of the things that are going on?

01:26:22.000 --> 01:26:30.000
Well, I'm going, I go to work in the Atlanta office and I get involved in the finance.

01:26:30.000 --> 01:26:40.000
First I'm doing the switchboard, then I'm helping Chessie Johnson, who is a SNCC bookkeeper in terms of the finances of that.

01:26:40.000 --> 01:26:46.000
So it's like we're receiving in all the checks in terms of donations and all of that that's being made.

01:26:46.000 --> 01:26:58.000
Now, I'm there in the Atlanta office at the same time when we, like, Stokely Carmichael called Michael, who I have grown to love and consider him like my brother and stuff,

01:26:58.000 --> 01:27:12.000
because he lived with my family when he's in Mississippi and stuff and all and doing the whole time in, no, we were talking about going into 66 when black power comes out.

01:27:12.000 --> 01:27:30.000
So it's no question about it. It's as a result of the shouting of black power on the Meredith March Against Fear, I experienced the direct process that's next money is just beginning to just really drop off.

01:27:30.000 --> 01:27:39.000
I mean, people are just very uptight about the money. I mean, they just, what does, I mean, it's the news meeting.

01:27:39.000 --> 01:27:54.000
What does, tell me what black power means. What does this, you know, and I definitely feel that the media definitely came after us in strong motions,

01:27:54.000 --> 01:28:23.000
that what are you all talking about with black power? I mean, what are you all going to set up a separate nation, you know, that was, in my opinion, one of the big changes in the whole process, you know, and then when Snick decided to, at one of the staff meetings, that the white staff people were working to work communities in the black, when they in the black community.

01:28:23.000 --> 01:28:39.000
I mean, the news plate is up much more than I think that the staff talked about it as. I mean, we basically talked about this is, these are the problems that we have.

01:28:39.000 --> 01:28:50.000
We have problems in the white community, we have problems in the black community, we feel that the problems in the black community will be better solved by black staff members working on it.

01:28:50.000 --> 01:29:01.000
And the white staff, we feel that they could contribute a lot more if they could help change some of the problems that we have in the white community.

01:29:01.000 --> 01:29:17.000
Were you on the, were you still on Snick's staff when Robert Parris Moses Zellner and Dottie Zellner made a proposal about staying on staff and working in the white community? I think this was in 1967.

01:29:17.000 --> 01:29:36.000
Well, I was still on staff, yeah, yeah, I actually left Snick in 1968, June of 1968, after, you know, King was killed in April. And I think pretty much by 68, we were beginning to, because the money was all gone.

01:29:36.000 --> 01:29:47.000
Do you remember their proposal? I'm not sure about that remembering that proposal. I do remember that, I mean, I know Robert Parris Moses and Daddy both quite well, yeah.

01:29:47.000 --> 01:29:48.000
Yeah.

01:29:48.000 --> 01:29:52.000
You mentioned that Stokey used to stay with your family.

01:29:52.000 --> 01:29:53.000
Yes.

01:29:53.000 --> 01:30:14.000
So, what do you like? Well, Stokey was a tall, dark, handsome young man. And, and, and, and he said, a very nice person and a personable person.

01:30:14.000 --> 01:30:26.000
I think I'm not sure whether it was joy or whether it was my brother, Dwight, one of them brought him home to, to our house in like in 62.

01:30:26.000 --> 01:30:43.000
And then from that point on, whenever Stokey was in Greenwood, he always stayed with my family. And he, my family did, I mean, you know, since I've known, I mean, families took in civil rights workers. That's how people worked, you know, so that,

01:30:43.000 --> 01:31:05.000
but Stokey was a regular stay at my family's house. I mean, he was always personable, you know. And, and he always talked about, you know, his family, you know, so it was like, and, and, and he used to talk about his group, the group of students that he worked with at Howard.

01:31:05.000 --> 01:31:18.000
So, when I knew him, he was going back with some folks. He would be in Mississippi in the summertime and back at Howard. He was telling me about, oh, he, when I told him I was going to go to work in McComb, Mississippi for the summer, six of, he said, oh, you're making a mistake.

01:31:18.000 --> 01:31:26.000
He said, I'm bringing back all my people and said that the whole,

01:31:26.000 --> 01:31:37.000
inverter content is love. Convert operational district is going to be just flooded with all of my NAG. And he said, you're going to want to be down there, you're going to be sorry.

01:31:37.000 --> 01:31:54.000
Yeah, but he could make himself at much at home with anybody. I mean, he could sit down and he could really talk to you.

01:31:54.000 --> 01:32:00.500
And not in a balloon way, and it was always trying to,

01:32:00.500 --> 01:32:05.260
no, it's always done encouragement and always to talk about,

01:32:05.260 --> 01:32:08.500
what we have in common, how we can do things

01:32:08.500 --> 01:32:10.820
to make a difference in the world.

01:32:10.820 --> 01:32:13.980
Well, you know, so you know all these college students

01:32:13.980 --> 01:32:16.060
like it to balloon, probably?

01:32:16.060 --> 01:32:17.620
And yo, yeah!

01:32:17.620 --> 01:32:20.740
But they didn't persuade you to go to school with them, right?

01:32:20.740 --> 01:32:21.860
No, no, no.

01:32:21.940 --> 01:32:24.780
I don't think they could have possibly been persuade.

01:32:24.780 --> 01:32:26.260
I wanted to leave the state.

01:32:26.260 --> 01:32:28.940
I want, I'm telling you, it's like,

01:32:30.020 --> 01:32:32.940
I mean, it's growing up in Mississippi

01:32:34.460 --> 01:32:39.460
and wanting to see what's out there in the rest of the world.

01:32:39.800 --> 01:32:43.460
And I think that that was one of the biggest things

01:32:43.460 --> 01:32:48.300
that impressed me the most is that when I met people like,

01:32:48.300 --> 01:32:50.800
now, I'm marrying right, Elemon, you know,

01:32:50.800 --> 01:32:54.720
all these people I'm meeting when I'm in high school.

01:32:54.720 --> 01:32:56.760
And they are from different places

01:32:56.760 --> 01:33:01.760
and they have done and are doing things now to help us.

01:33:02.720 --> 01:33:06.760
And I just see this as really making a difference.

01:33:06.760 --> 01:33:10.040
No, I had met both Joyce Ladner and Dorie Ann Ladner,

01:33:10.040 --> 01:33:12.640
who are also from Mississippi and stuff,

01:33:12.640 --> 01:33:14.960
but I had no interest in going to,

01:33:16.220 --> 01:33:17.400
to go into Gulu.

01:33:17.400 --> 01:33:19.120
And actually, one night,

01:33:19.120 --> 01:33:21.760
this is when I think about Dorie Ann Ladner is,

01:33:21.760 --> 01:33:25.000
this is, I mean, movement people make connections

01:33:25.000 --> 01:33:26.920
with people and they just have friends.

01:33:26.920 --> 01:33:28.580
And it's like,

01:33:28.580 --> 01:33:32.900
Stokely Carmichael and Dorie Ann Ladner are in New Orleans when I'm at Dillard.

01:33:33.840 --> 01:33:38.840
And it's after hours for girls to receive gifts.

01:33:39.160 --> 01:33:43.120
So they have come down for Mardi Gras, right?

01:33:43.120 --> 01:33:48.120
And so, so they decide that they know I'm there

01:33:48.840 --> 01:33:51.280
in school and they know I'm in the dormitory

01:33:51.280 --> 01:33:53.160
because it's after so late,

01:33:53.160 --> 01:33:55.520
you can't be anywhere but in the dormitory.

01:33:55.520 --> 01:33:58.560
So they come by to see me at the school.

01:33:58.560 --> 01:34:01.680
They tell the house mother at the dormitory

01:34:01.680 --> 01:34:03.840
that they are my sisters and brothers.

01:34:03.840 --> 01:34:07.580
And they come up, please.

01:34:09.360 --> 01:34:14.360
And she agreed to get sent up me for my room

01:34:14.360 --> 01:34:16.480
and I come down and all of a sudden,

01:34:16.480 --> 01:34:18.480
so I'm like, overwhelm.

01:34:18.480 --> 01:34:21.800
I'm just so happy to see Stokely Carmichael and Dorie Ann Ladner

01:34:21.800 --> 01:34:24.240
and they have come to visit me as my son.

01:34:24.240 --> 01:34:25.560
That's wonderful.

01:34:27.480 --> 01:34:31.440
I mean, that's the way movement people were, you know?

01:34:33.040 --> 01:34:34.760
So are there things that you would want people

01:34:34.760 --> 01:34:36.240
to know about the movement?

01:34:39.080 --> 01:34:44.080
I think that one of the biggest things that I found

01:34:44.240 --> 01:34:48.240
is that it had the ability to attract people

01:34:50.840 --> 01:34:54.400
from all facets of life.

01:34:54.400 --> 01:34:58.040
And everybody, Robert Parris Moses and Jim,

01:34:58.040 --> 01:35:00.560
and everybody that I came in contact with

01:35:00.560 --> 01:35:04.440
always tried to do things to help you

01:35:04.440 --> 01:35:08.480
and always tried to do things to help you

01:35:08.480 --> 01:35:11.760
expose other people to doing something

01:35:11.760 --> 01:35:13.400
to make a difference.

01:35:13.680 --> 01:35:16.640
And I never felt that anybody was looking

01:35:16.640 --> 01:35:21.320
for any personal advancement.

01:35:21.320 --> 01:35:24.520
It wasn't like, you know, I want to be the richest person.

01:35:24.520 --> 01:35:27.680
I want to do something to help somebody else.

01:35:27.680 --> 01:35:29.760
And I think that was the one of the things

01:35:29.760 --> 01:35:32.520
that impressed me the most about it.

01:35:32.520 --> 01:35:35.400
You know, I mean, I met Robert Parris Moses, no.

01:35:35.400 --> 01:35:37.680
I mean, you're talking about people who all

01:35:37.680 --> 01:35:41.960
who had possibilities to live, come to realize

01:35:41.960 --> 01:35:44.480
and yet they were willing to set this aside

01:35:44.480 --> 01:35:47.120
to come to help somebody else.

01:35:49.200 --> 01:35:50.200
Yeah, okay.

01:35:50.200 --> 01:35:51.640
We're sorry, are we gonna say something now?

01:35:51.640 --> 01:35:52.480
No.

01:35:52.480 --> 01:35:53.320
Okay.

01:35:53.320 --> 01:35:54.080
Thank you so much.

01:35:54.080 --> 01:35:55.320
Oh, thank you.

01:35:55.320 --> 01:35:56.480
Oh, my God.

01:35:56.480 --> 01:35:59.520
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress

01:35:59.520 --> 01:36:01.640
and the Smithsonian National Museum

01:36:01.640 --> 01:36:04.320
of African-American history and culture.

